G-OS-000458-GPOS-00203, SRG-OS-000463-GPOS-00207, SRG-OS-000468-GPOS-00212","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["V-93111","SV-103199","CCI-000172","CCI-002234"],"reference_identifier":"8207","uuid":"3378756b-304b-49c6-801d-e79feb63eb90","stig_uuid":"f79ea114-f8fc-4462-a57f-8e955b36a64c","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsServer2019_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 643E5D3FA6E450390E23A0A5E89799159B4DC21F\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'Windows Server 2019 must be configured to audit System - Other System Events failures.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the Windows Server 2019 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-205781","group_tree":[{"id":"V-205781","title":"SRG-OS-000327-GPOS-00127","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-205781","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000327-GPOS-00127","rule_id_src":"SV-205781r958732_rule","rule_id":"SV-205781","rule_version":"WN19-AU-000360","rule_title":"Windows Server 2019 must be configured to audit System - Security State Change successes.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Windows Settings >> Security Settings >> Advanced Audit Policy Configuration >> System Audit Policies >> System >> \"Audit Security State Change\" with \"Success\" selected.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Security Option \"Audit: Force audit policy subcategory settings (Windows Vista or later) to override audit policy category settings\" must be set to \"Enabled\" (WN19-SO-000050) for the detailed auditing subcategories to be effective. \n\nUse the \"AuditPol\" tool to review the current Audit Policy configuration:\n\nOpen \"PowerShell\" or a \"Command Prompt\" with elevated privileges (\"Run as administrator\").\n\nEnter \"AuditPol /get /category:*\"\n\nCompare the \"AuditPol\" settings with the following:\n\nIf the system does not audit the following, this is a finding.\n\nSystem >> Security State Change - Success","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Maintaining an audit trail of system activity logs can help identify configuration errors, troubleshoot service disruptions, and analyze compromises that have occurred, as well as detect attacks. Audit logs are necessary to provide a trail of evidence in case the system or network is compromised. Collecting this data is essential for analyzing the security of information assets and detecting signs of suspicious and unexpected behavior.\n\nSecurity State Change records events related to changes in the security state, such as startup and shutdown of the system.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000327-GPOS-00127, SRG-OS-000458-GPOS-00203, SRG-OS-000463-GPOS-00207, SRG-OS-000468-GPOS-00212","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["SV-103201","V-93113","CCI-000172","CCI-002234"],"reference_identifier":"8961","uuid":"928910ad-3258-4b71-9326-279bd039274e","stig_uuid":"f79ea114-f8fc-4462-a57f-8e955b36a64c","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsServer2019_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 69CA9F7995B670BCF70CBA521CBBEB0D259A229A\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'Windows Server 2019 must be configured to audit System - Security State Change successes.' matches the expected value on the Windows Server 2019 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-205782","group_tree":[{"id":"V-205782","title":"SRG-OS-000327-GPOS-00127","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-205782","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000327-GPOS-00127","rule_id_src":"SV-205782r958732_rule","rule_id":"SV-205782","rule_version":"WN19-AU-000370","rule_title":"Windows Server 2019 must be configured to audit System - Security System Extension successes.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Windows Settings >> Security Settings >> Advanced Audit Policy Configuration >> System Audit Policies >> System >> \"Audit Security System Extension\" with \"Success\" selected.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Security Option \"Audit: Force audit policy subcategory settings (Windows Vista or later) to override audit policy category settings\" must be set to \"Enabled\" (WN19-SO-000050) for the detailed auditing subcategories to be effective. \n\nUse the \"AuditPol\" tool to review the current Audit Policy configuration:\n\nOpen \"PowerShell\" or a \"Command Prompt\" with elevated privileges (\"Run as administrator\").\n\nEnter \"AuditPol /get /category:*\"\n\nCompare the \"AuditPol\" settings with the following:\n\nIf the system does not audit the following, this is a finding.\n\nSystem >> Security System Extension - Success","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Maintaining an audit trail of system activity logs can help identify configuration errors, troubleshoot service disruptions, and analyze compromises that have occurred, as well as detect attacks. Audit logs are necessary to provide a trail of evidence in case the system or network is compromised. Collecting this data is essential for analyzing the security of information assets and detecting signs of suspicious and unexpected behavior.\n\nSecurity System Extension records events related to extension code being loaded by the security subsystem.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000327-GPOS-00127, SRG-OS-000458-GPOS-00203, SRG-OS-000463-GPOS-00207, SRG-OS-000468-GPOS-00212","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["V-93115","SV-103203","CCI-000172","CCI-002234"],"reference_identifier":"7829","uuid":"b51e87a4-141d-4935-949e-1a87a7570330","stig_uuid":"f79ea114-f8fc-4462-a57f-8e955b36a64c","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsServer2019_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: CA8722F275ACFA350D96850B5AC502046380BFA4\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'Windows Server 2019 must be configured to audit System - Security System Extension successes.' matches the expected value on the Windows Server 2019 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-205783","group_tree":[{"id":"V-205783","title":"SRG-OS-000327-GPOS-00127","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-205783","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000327-GPOS-00127","rule_id_src":"SV-205783r958732_rule","rule_id":"SV-205783","rule_version":"WN19-AU-000380","rule_title":"Windows Server 2019 must be configured to audit System - System Integrity successes.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Windows Settings >> Security Settings >> Advanced Audit Policy Configuration >> System Audit Policies >> System >> \"Audit System Integrity\" with \"Success\" selected.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Security Option \"Audit: Force audit policy subcategory settings (Windows Vista or later) to override audit policy category settings\" must be set to \"Enabled\" (WN19-SO-000050) for the detailed auditing subcategories to be effective. \n\nUse the \"AuditPol\" tool to review the current Audit Policy configuration:\n\nOpen \"PowerShell\" or a \"Command Prompt\" with elevated privileges (\"Run as administrator\").\n\nEnter \"AuditPol /get /category:*\"\n\nCompare the \"AuditPol\" settings with the following:\n\nIf the system does not audit the following, this is a finding.\n\nSystem >> System Integrity - Success","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Maintaining an audit trail of system activity logs can help identify configuration errors, troubleshoot service disruptions, and analyze compromises that have occurred, as well as detect attacks. Audit logs are necessary to provide a trail of evidence in case the system or network is compromised. Collecting this data is essential for analyzing the security of information assets and detecting signs of suspicious and unexpected behavior.\n\nSystem Integrity records events related to violations of integrity to the security subsystem.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000327-GPOS-00127, SRG-OS-000471-GPOS-00215, SRG-OS-000471-GPOS-00216, SRG-OS-000477-GPOS-00222","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["V-93117","SV-103205","CCI-000172","CCI-002234"],"reference_identifier":"3618","uuid":"7c1087cd-9525-4eca-b6ee-7c8e09c25f5c","stig_uuid":"f79ea114-f8fc-4462-a57f-8e955b36a64c","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsServer2019_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 9DE24474582718F88DE17E568A40B6EF625ED5FD\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'Windows Server 2019 must be configured to audit System - System Integrity successes.' matches the expected value on the Windows Server 2019 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-205784","group_tree":[{"id":"V-205784","title":"SRG-OS-000327-GPOS-00127","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-205784","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000327-GPOS-00127","rule_id_src":"SV-205784r958732_rule","rule_id":"SV-205784","rule_version":"WN19-AU-000390","rule_title":"Windows Server 2019 must be configured to audit System - System Integrity failures.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Windows Settings >> Security Settings >> Advanced Audit Policy Configuration >> System Audit Policies >> System >> \"Audit System Integrity\" with \"Failure\" selected.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Security Option \"Audit: Force audit policy subcategory settings (Windows Vista or later) to override audit policy category settings\" must be set to \"Enabled\" (WN19-SO-000050) for the detailed auditing subcategories to be effective. \n\nUse the \"AuditPol\" tool to review the current Audit Policy configuration:\n\nOpen \"PowerShell\" or a \"Command Prompt\" with elevated privileges (\"Run as administrator\").\n\nEnter \"AuditPol /get /category:*\"\n\nCompare the \"AuditPol\" settings with the following:\n\nIf the system does not audit the following, this is a finding.\n\nSystem >> System Integrity - Failure","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Maintaining an audit trail of system activity logs can help identify configuration errors, troubleshoot service disruptions, and analyze compromises that have occurred, as well as detect attacks. Audit logs are necessary to provide a trail of evidence in case the system or network is compromised. Collecting this data is essential for analyzing the security of information assets and detecting signs of suspicious and unexpected behavior.\n\nSystem Integrity records events related to violations of integrity to the security subsystem.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000327-GPOS-00127, SRG-OS-000471-GPOS-00215, SRG-OS-000471-GPOS-00216, SRG-OS-000477-GPOS-00222","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["V-93119","SV-103207","CCI-000172","CCI-002234"],"reference_identifier":"5282","uuid":"9b38d3e2-4d45-40af-8b74-3905efdba740","stig_uuid":"f79ea114-f8fc-4462-a57f-8e955b36a64c","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsServer2019_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 5C79DC6156DAFFDE25042B5E14D9E837F6CE87A7\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'Windows Server 2019 must be configured to audit System - System Integrity failures.' matches the expected value on the Windows Server 2019 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-205785","group_tree":[{"id":"V-205785","title":"SRG-OS-000327-GPOS-00127","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-205785","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000327-GPOS-00127","rule_id_src":"SV-205785r958732_rule","rule_id":"SV-205785","rule_version":"WN19-DC-000170","rule_title":"Windows Server 2019 Active Directory Group Policy objects must be configured with proper audit settings.","fix_text":"Configure the audit settings for Group Policy objects to include the following:\n\nThis can be done at the Policy level in Active Directory to apply to all group policies.\n\nOpen \"Active Directory Users and Computers\" (available from various menus or run \"dsa.msc\").\n\nSelect \"Advanced Features\" from the \"View\" Menu.\n\nNavigate to [Domain] >> System >> Policies in the left panel.\n\nRight click \"Policies\", select \"Properties\".\n\nSelect the \"Security\" tab.\n\nSelect the \"Advanced\" button.\n\nSelect the \"Auditing\" tab.\n\nType - Fail\nPrincipal - Everyone\nAccess - Full Control\nApplies to - This object and all descendant objects or Descendant groupPolicyContainer objects\n\nThe three Success types listed below are defaults inherited from the Parent Object. Where Special is listed in the summary screens for Access, detailed Permissions are provided for reference.\n\nType - Success\nPrincipal - Everyone\nAccess - Special (Permissions: Write all properties, Modify permissions; Properties: all \"Write\" type selected)\nInherited from - Parent Object\nApplies to - Descendant groupPolicyContainer objects\n\nTwo instances with the following summary information will be listed:\n\nType - Success\nPrincipal - Everyone\nAccess - blank (Permissions: none selected; Properties: one instance - Write gPLink, one instance - Write gPOptions)\nInherited from - Parent Object\nApplies to - Descendant Organization Unit Objects","weight":"10.0","check_content":"This applies to domain controllers. It is NA for other systems.\n\nReview the auditing configuration for all Group Policy objects.\n\nOpen \"Group Policy Management\" (available from various menus or run \"gpmc.msc\").\n\nNavigate to \"Group Policy Objects\" in the domain being reviewed (Forest >> Domains >> Domain).\n\nFor each Group Policy object:\n\nSelect the Group Policy object item in the left pane.\n\nSelect the \"Delegation\" tab in the right pane.\n\nSelect the \"Advanced\" button.\n\nSelect the \"Advanced\" button again and then the \"Auditing\" tab.\n\nIf the audit settings for any Group Policy object are not at least as inclusive as those below, this is a finding:\n\nType - Fail\nPrincipal - Everyone\nAccess - Full Control\nApplies to - This object and all descendant objects or Descendant groupPolicyContainer objects\n\nThe three Success types listed below are defaults inherited from the Parent Object. Where Special is listed in the summary screens for Access, detailed Permissions are provided for reference.\n\nType - Success\nPrincipal - Everyone\nAccess - Special (Permissions: Write all properties, Modify permissions; Properties: all \"Write\" type selected)\nInherited from - Parent Object\nApplies to - Descendant groupPolicyContainer objects\n\nTwo instances with the following summary information will be listed:\n\nType - Success\nPrincipal - Everyone\nAccess - blank (Permissions: none selected; Properties: one instance - Write gPLink, one instance - Write gPOptions)\nInherited from - Parent Object\nApplies to - Descendant Organization Unit Objects","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"When inappropriate audit settings are configured for directory service database objects, it may be possible for a user or process to update the data without generating any tracking data. The impact of missing audit data is related to the type of object. A failure to capture audit data for objects used by identification, authentication, or authorization functions could degrade or eliminate the ability to track changes to access policy for systems or data. \n\nFor Active Directory (AD), there are a number of critical object types in the domain naming context of the AD database for which auditing is essential. This includes Group Policy objects. Because changes to these objects can significantly impact access controls or the availability of systems, the absence of auditing data makes it impossible to identify the source of changes that impact the confidentiality, integrity, and availability of data and systems throughout an AD domain. The lack of proper auditing can result in insufficient forensic evidence needed to investigate an incident and prosecute the intruder.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000327-GPOS-00127, SRG-OS-000458-GPOS-00203, SRG-OS-000463-GPOS-00207, SRG-OS-000468-GPOS-00212","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["V-93121","SV-103209","CCI-000172","CCI-002234"],"reference_identifier":"3799","uuid":"b548fcac-79c4-4205-9d10-c78747e4baa7","stig_uuid":"f79ea114-f8fc-4462-a57f-8e955b36a64c","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsServer2019_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: A66984B2A385BFB5D91E4FB3FFAB5540A51D3FB2\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'Windows Server 2019 Active Directory Group Policy objects must be configured with proper audit settings.' matches the expected value on the Windows Server 2019 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-205786","group_tree":[{"id":"V-205786","title":"SRG-OS-000327-GPOS-00127","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-205786","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000327-GPOS-00127","rule_id_src":"SV-205786r958732_rule","rule_id":"SV-205786","rule_version":"WN19-DC-000180","rule_title":"Windows Server 2019 Active Directory Domain object must be configured with proper audit settings.","fix_text":"Open \"Active Directory Users and Computers\" (available from various menus or run \"dsa.msc\").\n\nEnsure \"Advanced Features\" is selected in the \"View\" menu.\n\nSelect the domain being reviewed in the left pane.\n\nRight-click the domain name and select \"Properties\".\n\nSelect the \"Security\" tab.\n\nSelect the \"Advanced\" button and then the \"Auditing\" tab.\n\nConfigure the audit settings for Domain object to include the following:\n\nType - Fail\nPrincipal - Everyone\nAccess - Full Control\nInherited from - None\nApplies to - This object only\n\nThe success types listed below are defaults. Where Special is listed in the summary screens for Access, detailed Permissions are provided for reference. Various Properties selections may also exist by default.\n\nTwo instances with the following summary information will be listed:\n\nType - Success\nPrincipal - Everyone\nAccess - (blank)\nInherited from - None\nApplies to - Special\n\nType - Success\nPrincipal - Domain Users\nAccess - All extended rights\nInherited from - None\nApplies to - This object only\n\nType - Success\nPrincipal - Administrators\nAccess - All extended rights\nInherited from - None\nApplies to - This object only\n\nType - Success\nPrincipal - Everyone\nAccess - Special\nInherited from - None\nApplies to - This object only\n(Access - Special = Permissions: Write all properties, Modify permissions, Modify owner.)","weight":"10.0","check_content":"This applies to domain controllers. It is NA for other systems.\n\nReview the auditing configuration for the Domain object.\n\nOpen \"Active Directory Users and Computers\" (available from various menus or run \"dsa.msc\").\n\nEnsure \"Advanced Features\" is selected in the \"View\" menu.\n\nSelect the domain being reviewed in the left pane.\n\nRight-click the domain name and select \"Properties\".\n\nSelect the \"Security\" tab.\n\nSelect the \"Advanced\" button and then the \"Auditing\" tab.\n\nIf the audit settings on the Domain object are not at least as inclusive as those below, this is a finding:\n\nType - Fail\nPrincipal - Everyone\nAccess - Full Control\nInherited from - None\nApplies to - This object only\n\nThe success types listed below are defaults. Where Special is listed in the summary screens for Access, detailed Permissions are provided for reference. Various Properties selections may also exist by default.\n\nTwo instances with the following summary information will be listed:\n\nType - Success\nPrincipal - Everyone\nAccess - (blank)\nInherited from - None\nApplies to - Special\n\nType - Success\nPrincipal - Domain Users\nAccess - All extended rights\nInherited from - None\nApplies to - This object only\n\nType - Success\nPrincipal - Administrators\nAccess - All extended rights\nInherited from - None\nApplies to - This object only\n\nType - Success\nPrincipal - Everyone\nAccess - Special\nInherited from - None\nApplies to - This object only\n(Access - Special = Permissions: Write all properties, Modify permissions, Modify owner)","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"When inappropriate audit settings are configured for directory service database objects, it may be possible for a user or process to update the data without generating any tracking data. The impact of missing audit data is related to the type of object. A failure to capture audit data for objects used by identification, authentication, or authorization functions could degrade or eliminate the ability to track changes to access policy for systems or data. \n\nFor Active Directory (AD), there are a number of critical object types in the domain naming context of the AD database for which auditing is essential. This includes the Domain object. Because changes to these objects can significantly impact access controls or the availability of systems, the absence of auditing data makes it impossible to identify the source of changes that impact the confidentiality, integrity, and availability of data and systems throughout an AD domain. The lack of proper auditing can result in insufficient forensic evidence needed to investigate an incident and prosecute the intruder.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000327-GPOS-00127, SRG-OS-000458-GPOS-00203, SRG-OS-000463-GPOS-00207, SRG-OS-000468-GPOS-00212","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["SV-103211","V-93123","CCI-000172","CCI-002234"],"reference_identifier":"6411","uuid":"96241c76-e846-425d-bc04-bcbf10191f3c","stig_uuid":"f79ea114-f8fc-4462-a57f-8e955b36a64c","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsServer2019_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: D1B2C789373919ADF6DCF5ACB994B2DE41F28096\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'Windows Server 2019 Active Directory Domain object must be configured with proper audit settings.' matches the expected value on the Windows Server 2019 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-205787","group_tree":[{"id":"V-205787","title":"SRG-OS-000327-GPOS-00127","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-205787","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000327-GPOS-00127","rule_id_src":"SV-205787r958732_rule","rule_id":"SV-205787","rule_version":"WN19-DC-000190","rule_title":"Windows Server 2019 Active Directory Infrastructure object must be configured with proper audit settings.","fix_text":"Open \"Active Directory Users and Computers\" (available from various menus or run \"dsa.msc\").\n\nEnsure \"Advanced Features\" is selected in the \"View\" menu.\n\nSelect the domain being reviewed in the left pane.\n\nRight-click the \"Infrastructure\" object in the right pane and select \"Properties\".\n\nSelect the \"Security\" tab.\n\nSelect the \"Advanced\" button and then the \"Auditing\" tab.\n\nConfigure the audit settings for Infrastructure object to include the following:\n\nType - Fail\nPrincipal - Everyone\nAccess - Full Control\nInherited from - None\n\nThe success types listed below are defaults. Where Special is listed in the summary screens for Access, detailed Permissions are provided for reference. Various Properties selections may also exist by default.\n\nType - Success\nPrincipal - Everyone\nAccess - Special\nInherited from - None\n(Access - Special = Permissions: Write all properties, All extended rights, Change infrastructure master)\n\nTwo instances with the following summary information will be listed:\n\nType - Success\nPrincipal - Everyone\nAccess - (blank)\nInherited from - (CN of domain)","weight":"10.0","check_content":"This applies to domain controllers. It is NA for other systems.\n\nReview the auditing configuration for Infrastructure object.\n\nOpen \"Active Directory Users and Computers\" (available from various menus or run \"dsa.msc\").\n\nEnsure \"Advanced Features\" is selected in the \"View\" menu.\n\nSelect the domain being reviewed in the left pane.\n\nRight-click the \"Infrastructure\" object in the right pane and select \"Properties\".\n\nSelect the \"Security\" tab.\n\nSelect the \"Advanced\" button and then the \"Auditing\" tab.\n\nIf the audit settings on the Infrastructure object are not at least as inclusive as those below, this is a finding:\n\nType - Fail\nPrincipal - Everyone\nAccess - Full Control\nInherited from - None\n\nThe success types listed below are defaults. Where Special is listed in the summary screens for Access, detailed Permissions are provided for reference. Various Properties selections may also exist by default.\n\nType - Success\nPrincipal - Everyone\nAccess - Special\nInherited from - None\n(Access - Special = Permissions: Write all properties, All extended rights, Change infrastructure master)\n\nTwo instances with the following summary information will be listed:\n\nType - Success\nPrincipal - Everyone\nAccess - (blank)\nInherited from - (CN of domain)","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"When inappropriate audit settings are configured for directory service database objects, it may be possible for a user or process to update the data without generating any tracking data. The impact of missing audit data is related to the type of object. A failure to capture audit data for objects used by identification, authentication, or authorization functions could degrade or eliminate the ability to track changes to access policy for systems or data. \n\nFor Active Directory (AD), there are a number of critical object types in the domain naming context of the AD database for which auditing is essential. This includes the Infrastructure object. Because changes to these objects can significantly impact access controls or the availability of systems, the absence of auditing data makes it impossible to identify the source of changes that impact the confidentiality, integrity, and availability of data and systems throughout an AD domain. The lack of proper auditing can result in insufficient forensic evidence needed to investigate an incident and prosecute the intruder.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000327-GPOS-00127, SRG-OS-000458-GPOS-00203, SRG-OS-000463-GPOS-00207, SRG-OS-000468-GPOS-00212","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["SV-103213","V-93125","CCI-000172","CCI-002234"],"reference_identifier":"4953","uuid":"c00ab1ff-e841-4c25-9fba-6a7cad5fa5b5","stig_uuid":"f79ea114-f8fc-4462-a57f-8e955b36a64c","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsServer2019_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 9DAACCDB2ECC6F27EBDF3CF95D7828A4D61F6230\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'Windows Server 2019 Active Directory Infrastructure object must be configured with proper audit settings.' matches the expected value on the Windows Server 2019 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-205788","group_tree":[{"id":"V-205788","title":"SRG-OS-000327-GPOS-00127","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-205788","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000327-GPOS-00127","rule_id_src":"SV-205788r958732_rule","rule_id":"SV-205788","rule_version":"WN19-DC-000200","rule_title":"Windows Server 2019 Active Directory Domain Controllers Organizational Unit (OU) object must be configured with proper audit settings.","fix_text":"Open \"Active Directory Users and Computers\" (available from various menus or run \"dsa.msc\").\n\nEnsure \"Advanced Features\" is selected in the \"View\" menu.\n\nSelect the \"Domain Controllers OU\" under the domain being reviewed in the left pane.\n\nRight-click the \"Domain Controllers OU\" object and select \"Properties\".\n\nSelect the \"Security\" tab.\n\nSelect the \"Advanced\" button and then the \"Auditing\" tab.\n\nConfigure the audit settings for Domain Controllers OU object to include the following:\n\nType - Fail\nPrincipal - Everyone\nAccess - Full Control\nInherited from - None\n\nThe success types listed below are defaults. Where Special is listed in the summary screens for Access, detailed Permissions are provided for reference. Various Properties selections may also exist by default.\n\nType - Success\nPrincipal - Everyone\nAccess - Special\nInherited from - None\nApplies to - This object only\n(Access - Special = Permissions: all create, delete and modify permissions)\n\nType - Success\nPrincipal - Everyone\nAccess - Write all properties\nInherited from - None\nApplies to - This object and all descendant objects\n\nTwo instances with the following summary information will be listed:\n\nType - Success\nPrincipal - Everyone\nAccess - (blank)\nInherited from - (CN of domain)\nApplies to - Descendant Organizational Unit objects","weight":"10.0","check_content":"This applies to domain controllers. It is NA for other systems.\n\nReview the auditing configuration for the Domain Controller OU object.\n\nOpen \"Active Directory Users and Computers\" (available from various menus or run \"dsa.msc\").\n\nEnsure \"Advanced Features\" is selected in the \"View\" menu.\n\nSelect the \"Domain Controllers OU\" under the domain being reviewed in the left pane.\n\nRight-click the \"Domain Controllers OU\" object and select \"Properties\".\n\nSelect the \"Security\" tab.\n\nSelect the \"Advanced\" button and then the \"Auditing\" tab.\n\nIf the audit settings on the Domain Controllers OU object are not at least as inclusive as those below, this is a finding:\n\nType - Fail\nPrincipal - Everyone\nAccess - Full Control\nInherited from - None\nApplies to - This object and all descendant objects\n\nThe success types listed below are defaults. Where Special is listed in the summary screens for Access, detailed Permissions are provided for reference. Various Properties selections may also exist by default.\n\nType - Success\nPrincipal - Everyone\nAccess - Special\nInherited from - None\nApplies to - This object only\n(Access - Special = Permissions: all create, delete and modify permissions)\n\nType - Success\nPrincipal - Everyone\nAccess - Write all properties\nInherited from - None\nApplies to - This object and all descendant objects\n\nTwo instances with the following summary information will be listed:\n\nType - Success\nPrincipal - Everyone\nAccess - (blank)\nInherited from - (CN of domain)\nApplies to - Descendant Organizational Unit objects","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"When inappropriate audit settings are configured for directory service database objects, it may be possible for a user or process to update the data without generating any tracking data. The impact of missing audit data is related to the type of object. A failure to capture audit data for objects used by identification, authentication, or authorization functions could degrade or eliminate the ability to track changes to access policy for systems or data. \n\nFor Active Directory (AD), there are a number of critical object types in the domain naming context of the AD database for which auditing is essential. This includes the Domain Controller OU object. Because changes to these objects can significantly impact access controls or the availability of systems, the absence of auditing data makes it impossible to identify the source of changes that impact the confidentiality, integrity, and availability of data and systems throughout an AD domain. The lack of proper auditing can result in insufficient forensic evidence needed to investigate an incident and prosecute the intruder.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000327-GPOS-00127, SRG-OS-000458-GPOS-00203, SRG-OS-000463-GPOS-00207, SRG-OS-000468-GPOS-00212","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["SV-103215","V-93127","CCI-000172","CCI-002234"],"reference_identifier":"8460","uuid":"5d7da061-d7be-43d5-a318-2703e4d17dbe","stig_uuid":"f79ea114-f8fc-4462-a57f-8e955b36a64c","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsServer2019_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: B460F5D04495C0B9E032C016638BEE200779132D\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'Windows Server 2019 Active Directory Domain Controllers Organizational Unit (OU) object must be configured with proper audit settings.' matches the expected value on the Windows Server 2019 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-205789","group_tree":[{"id":"V-205789","title":"SRG-OS-000327-GPOS-00127","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-205789","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000327-GPOS-00127","rule_id_src":"SV-205789r958732_rule","rule_id":"SV-205789","rule_version":"WN19-DC-000210","rule_title":"Windows Server 2019 Active Directory AdminSDHolder object must be configured with proper audit settings.","fix_text":"Open \"Active Directory Users and Computers\" (available from various menus or run \"dsa.msc\").\n\nEnsure \"Advanced Features\" is selected in the \"View\" menu.\n\nSelect \"System\" under the domain being reviewed in the left pane.\n\nRight-click the \"AdminSDHolder\" object in the right pane and select \"Properties\".\n\nSelect the \"Security\" tab.\n\nSelect the \"Advanced\" button and then the \"Auditing\" tab.\n\nConfigure the audit settings for AdminSDHolder object to include the following:\n\nType - Fail\nPrincipal - Everyone\nAccess - Full Control\nInherited from - None\nApplies to - This object only\n\nThe success types listed below are defaults. Where Special is listed in the summary screens for Access, detailed Permissions are provided for reference. Various Properties selections may also exist by default.\n\nType - Success\nPrincipal - Everyone\nAccess - Special\nInherited from - None\nApplies to - This object only\n(Access - Special = Write all properties, Modify permissions, Modify owner)\n\nTwo instances with the following summary information will be listed:\n\nType - Success\nPrincipal - Everyone\nAccess - (blank)\nInherited from - (CN of domain)\nApplies to - Descendant Organizational Unit objects","weight":"10.0","check_content":"This applies to domain controllers. It is NA for other systems.\n\nReview the auditing configuration for the \"AdminSDHolder\" object.\n\nOpen \"Active Directory Users and Computers\" (available from various menus or run \"dsa.msc\").\n\nEnsure \"Advanced Features\" is selected in the \"View\" menu.\n\nSelect \"System\" under the domain being reviewed in the left pane.\n\nRight-click the \"AdminSDHolder\" object in the right pane and select \"Properties\".\n\nSelect the \"Security\" tab.\n\nSelect the \"Advanced\" button and then the \"Auditing\" tab.\n\nIf the audit settings on the \"AdminSDHolder\" object are not at least as inclusive as those below, this is a finding:\n\nType - Fail\nPrincipal - Everyone\nAccess - Full Control\nInherited from - None\nApplies to - This object only\n\nThe success types listed below are defaults. Where Special is listed in the summary screens for Access, detailed Permissions are provided for reference. Various Properties selections may also exist by default.\n\nType - Success\nPrincipal - Everyone\nAccess - Special\nInherited from - None\nApplies to - This object only\n(Access - Special = Write all properties, Modify permissions, Modify owner)\n\nTwo instances with the following summary information will be listed:\n\nType - Success\nPrincipal - Everyone\nAccess - (blank)\nInherited from - (CN of domain)\nApplies to - Descendant Organizational Unit objects","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"When inappropriate audit settings are configured for directory service database objects, it may be possible for a user or process to update the data without generating any tracking data. The impact of missing audit data is related to the type of object. A failure to capture audit data for objects used by identification, authentication, or authorization functions could degrade or eliminate the ability to track changes to access policy for systems or data. \n\nFor Active Directory (AD), there are a number of critical object types in the domain naming context of the AD database for which auditing is essential. This includes the AdminSDHolder object. Because changes to these objects can significantly impact access controls or the availability of systems, the absence of auditing data makes it impossible to identify the source of changes that impact the confidentiality, integrity, and availability of data and systems throughout an AD domain. The lack of proper auditing can result in insufficient forensic evidence needed to investigate an incident and prosecute the intruder.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000327-GPOS-00127, SRG-OS-000458-GPOS-00203, SRG-OS-000463-GPOS-00207, SRG-OS-000468-GPOS-00212","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["SV-103217","V-93129","CCI-000172","CCI-002234"],"reference_identifier":"5760","uuid":"c2c3c55f-a691-4cb4-95ad-65ccfaa788e5","stig_uuid":"f79ea114-f8fc-4462-a57f-8e955b36a64c","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsServer2019_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 004D9967AF3840BD9E513CD16007957D116CF7B1\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'Windows Server 2019 Active Directory AdminSDHolder object must be configured with proper audit settings.' matches the expected value on the Windows Server 2019 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-205790","group_tree":[{"id":"V-205790","title":"SRG-OS-000327-GPOS-00127","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-205790","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000327-GPOS-00127","rule_id_src":"SV-205790r958732_rule","rule_id":"SV-205790","rule_version":"WN19-DC-000220","rule_title":"Windows Server 2019 Active Directory RID Manager$ object must be configured with proper audit settings.","fix_text":"Open \"Active Directory Users and Computers\" (available from various menus or run \"dsa.msc\").\n\nEnsure \"Advanced Features\" is selected in the \"View\" menu.\n\nSelect \"System\" under the domain being reviewed in the left pane.\n\nRight-click the \"RID Manager$\" object in the right pane and select \"Properties\".\n\nSelect the \"Security\" tab.\n\nSelect the \"Advanced\" button and then the \"Auditing\" tab.\n\nConfigure the audit settings for RID Manager$ object to include the following:\n\nType - Fail\nPrincipal - Everyone\nAccess - Full Control\nInherited from - None\n\nThe success types listed below are defaults. Where Special is listed in the summary screens for Access, detailed Permissions are provided for reference. Various Properties selections may also exist by default.\n\nType - Success\nPrincipal - Everyone\nAccess - Special\nInherited from - None\n (Access - Special = Write all properties, All extended rights, Change RID master)\n\nTwo instances with the following summary information will be listed:\n\nType - Success\nPrincipal - Everyone\nAccess - (blank)\nInherited from - (CN of domain)","weight":"10.0","check_content":"This applies to domain controllers. It is NA for other systems.\n\nReview the auditing configuration for the \"RID Manager$\" object.\n\nOpen \"Active Directory Users and Computers\" (available from various menus or run \"dsa.msc\").\n\nEnsure \"Advanced Features\" is selected in the \"View\" menu.\n\nSelect \"System\" under the domain being reviewed in the left pane.\n\nRight-click the \"RID Manager$\" object in the right pane and select \"Properties\".\n\nSelect the \"Security\" tab.\n\nSelect the \"Advanced\" button and then the \"Auditing\" tab.\n\nIf the audit settings on the \"RID Manager$\" object are not at least as inclusive as those below, this is a finding:\n\nType - Fail\nPrincipal - Everyone\nAccess - Full Control\nInherited from - None\n\nThe success types listed below are defaults. Where Special is listed in the summary screens for Access, detailed Permissions are provided for reference. Various Properties selections may also exist by default.\n\nType - Success\nPrincipal - Everyone\nAccess - Special\nInherited from - None\n (Access - Special = Write all properties, All extended rights, Change RID master)\n\nTwo instances with the following summary information will be listed:\n\nType - Success\nPrincipal - Everyone\nAccess - (blank)\nInherited from - (CN of domain)","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"When inappropriate audit settings are configured for directory service database objects, it may be possible for a user or process to update the data without generating any tracking data. The impact of missing audit data is related to the type of object. A failure to capture audit data for objects used by identification, authentication, or authorization functions could degrade or eliminate the ability to track changes to access policy for systems or data. \n\nFor Active Directory (AD), there are a number of critical object types in the domain naming context of the AD database for which auditing is essential. This includes the RID Manager$ object. Because changes to these objects can significantly impact access controls or the availability of systems, the absence of auditing data makes it impossible to identify the source of changes that impact the confidentiality, integrity, and availability of data and systems throughout an AD domain. The lack of proper auditing can result in insufficient forensic evidence needed to investigate an incident and prosecute the intruder.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000327-GPOS-00127, SRG-OS-000458-GPOS-00203, SRG-OS-000463-GPOS-00207, SRG-OS-000468-GPOS-00212","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["V-93131","SV-103219","CCI-000172","CCI-002234"],"reference_identifier":"7869","uuid":"bf1314e1-edb7-455c-a1d1-17171964653b","stig_uuid":"f79ea114-f8fc-4462-a57f-8e955b36a64c","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsServer2019_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 735C3C770476723C144ED4D1F79746DC9DFA1200\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'Windows Server 2019 Active Directory RID Manager$ object must be configured with proper audit settings.' matches the expected value on the Windows Server 2019 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-205791","group_tree":[{"id":"V-205791","title":"SRG-OS-000327-GPOS-00127","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-205791","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000327-GPOS-00127","rule_id_src":"SV-205791r958732_rule","rule_id":"SV-205791","rule_version":"WN19-DC-000240","rule_title":"Windows Server 2019 must be configured to audit DS Access - Directory Service Access successes.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Windows Settings >> Security Settings >> Advanced Audit Policy Configuration >> System Audit Policies >> DS Access >> \"Directory Service Access\" with \"Success\" selected.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"This applies to domain controllers. It is NA for other systems.\n\nSecurity Option \"Audit: Force audit policy subcategory settings (Windows Vista or later) to override audit policy category settings\" must be set to \"Enabled\" (WN19-SO-000050) for the detailed auditing subcategories to be effective. \n\nUse the \"AuditPol\" tool to review the current Audit Policy configuration:\n\nOpen \"PowerShell\" or a \"Command Prompt\" with elevated privileges (\"Run as administrator\").\n\nEnter \"AuditPol /get /category:*\"\n\nCompare the \"AuditPol\" settings with the following:\n\nIf the system does not audit the following, this is a finding.\n\nDS Access >> Directory Service Access - Success","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Maintaining an audit trail of system activity logs can help identify configuration errors, troubleshoot service disruptions, and analyze compromises that have occurred, as well as detect attacks. Audit logs are necessary to provide a trail of evidence in case the system or network is compromised. Collecting this data is essential for analyzing the security of information assets and detecting signs of suspicious and unexpected behavior.\n\nAudit Directory Service Access records events related to users accessing an Active Directory object.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000327-GPOS-00127, SRG-OS-000458-GPOS-00203, SRG-OS-000463-GPOS-00207, SRG-OS-000468-GPOS-00212","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["SV-103221","V-93133","CCI-000172","CCI-002234"],"reference_identifier":"4964","uuid":"23341d32-08b6-4a82-9dad-fb76259174e4","stig_uuid":"f79ea114-f8fc-4462-a57f-8e955b36a64c","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsServer2019_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 3F141D373BD862FFF7A34E71A4ADCA27EEAB3674\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'Windows Server 2019 must be configured to audit DS Access - Directory Service Access successes.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the Windows Server 2019 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-205792","group_tree":[{"id":"V-205792","title":"SRG-OS-000327-GPOS-00127","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-205792","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000327-GPOS-00127","rule_id_src":"SV-205792r958732_rule","rule_id":"SV-205792","rule_version":"WN19-DC-000250","rule_title":"Windows Server 2019 must be configured to audit DS Access - Directory Service Access failures.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Windows Settings >> Security Settings >> Advanced Audit Policy Configuration >> System Audit Policies >> DS Access >> \"Directory Service Access\" with \"Failure\" selected.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"This applies to domain controllers. It is NA for other systems.\n\nSecurity Option \"Audit: Force audit policy subcategory settings (Windows Vista or later) to override audit policy category settings\" must be set to \"Enabled\" (WN19-SO-000050) for the detailed auditing subcategories to be effective. \n\nUse the \"AuditPol\" tool to review the current Audit Policy configuration:\n\nOpen \"PowerShell\" or a \"Command Prompt\" with elevated privileges (\"Run as administrator\").\n\nEnter \"AuditPol /get /category:*\"\n\nCompare the \"AuditPol\" settings with the following:\n\nIf the system does not audit the following, this is a finding.\n\nDS Access >> Directory Service Access - Failure","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Maintaining an audit trail of system activity logs can help identify configuration errors, troubleshoot service disruptions, and analyze compromises that have occurred, as well as detect attacks. Audit logs are necessary to provide a trail of evidence in case the system or network is compromised. Collecting this data is essential for analyzing the security of information assets and detecting signs of suspicious and unexpected behavior.\n\nAudit Directory Service Access records events related to users accessing an Active Directory object.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000327-GPOS-00127, SRG-OS-000458-GPOS-00203, SRG-OS-000463-GPOS-00207, SRG-OS-000468-GPOS-00212","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["SV-103223","V-93135","CCI-000172","CCI-002234"],"reference_identifier":"6488","uuid":"34208a4b-4704-4edb-8b29-76904ea1ff0e","stig_uuid":"f79ea114-f8fc-4462-a57f-8e955b36a64c","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsServer2019_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 7518A1F62648235243D0580474B48487911250C5\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'Windows Server 2019 must be configured to audit DS Access - Directory Service Access failures.' matches the expected value on the Windows Server 2019 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-205793","group_tree":[{"id":"V-205793","title":"SRG-OS-000327-GPOS-00127","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-205793","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000327-GPOS-00127","rule_id_src":"SV-205793r958732_rule","rule_id":"SV-205793","rule_version":"WN19-DC-000260","rule_title":"Windows Server 2019 must be configured to audit DS Access - Directory Service Changes successes.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Windows Settings >> Security Settings >> Advanced Audit Policy Configuration >> System Audit Policies >> DS Access >> \"Directory Service Changes\" with \"Success\" selected.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"This applies to domain controllers. It is NA for other systems.\n\nSecurity Option \"Audit: Force audit policy subcategory settings (Windows Vista or later) to override audit policy category settings\" must be set to \"Enabled\" (WN19-SO-000050) for the detailed auditing subcategories to be effective. \n\nUse the \"AuditPol\" tool to review the current Audit Policy configuration:\n\nOpen \"PowerShell\" or a \"Command Prompt\" with elevated privileges (\"Run as administrator\").\n\nEnter \"AuditPol /get /category:*\"\n\nCompare the \"AuditPol\" settings with the following:\n\nIf the system does not audit the following, this is a finding.\n\nDS Access >> Directory Service Changes - Success","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Maintaining an audit trail of system activity logs can help identify configuration errors, troubleshoot service disruptions, and analyze compromises that have occurred, as well as detect attacks. Audit logs are necessary to provide a trail of evidence in case the system or network is compromised. Collecting this data is essential for analyzing the security of information assets and detecting signs of suspicious and unexpected behavior.\n\nAudit Directory Service Changes records events related to changes made to objects in Active Directory Domain Services.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000327-GPOS-00127, SRG-OS-000458-GPOS-00203, SRG-OS-000463-GPOS-00207, SRG-OS-000468-GPOS-00212","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["V-93137","SV-103225","CCI-000172","CCI-002234"],"reference_identifier":"6324","uuid":"990f66fc-8ffb-40f5-b0ba-34b9f1beb202","stig_uuid":"f79ea114-f8fc-4462-a57f-8e955b36a64c","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"Not applicable - capability not installed/enabled on this asset.","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsServer2019_Checks) marked this Not_Applicable on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 99554B0D62A496A7059E367BA732F0F64A7A0FF5\r\n~~~~~\r\nThe feature/role addressed by 'Windows Server 2019 must be configured to audit DS Access - Directory Service Changes successes.' is not present or not in use on this the Windows Server 2019 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-205795","group_tree":[{"id":"V-205795","title":"SRG-OS-000329-GPOS-00128","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-205795","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000329-GPOS-00128","rule_id_src":"SV-205795r958736_rule","rule_id":"SV-205795","rule_version":"WN19-AC-000010","rule_title":"Windows Server 2019 account lockout duration must be configured to 15 minutes or greater.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Windows Settings >> Security Settings >> Account Policies >> Account Lockout Policy >> \"Account lockout duration\" to \"15\" minutes or greater.\n\nA value of \"0\" is also acceptable, requiring an administrator to unlock the account.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the effective setting in Local Group Policy Editor.\n\nRun \"gpedit.msc\".\n\nNavigate to Local Computer Policy >> Computer Configuration >> Windows Settings >> Security Settings >> Account Policies >> Account Lockout Policy.\n\nIf the \"Account lockout duration\" is less than \"15\" minutes (excluding \"0\"), this is a finding.\n\nFor server core installations, run the following command:\n\nSecedit /Export /Areas SecurityPolicy /CFG C:\\Path\\FileName.Txt\n\nIf \"LockoutDuration\" is less than \"15\" (excluding \"0\") in the file, this is a finding.\n\nConfiguring this to \"0\", requiring an administrator to unlock the account, is more restrictive and is not a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"The account lockout feature, when enabled, prevents brute-force password attacks on the system. This parameter specifies the period of time that an account will remain locked after the specified number of failed logon attempts.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["V-93145","SV-103233","CCI-002238"],"reference_identifier":"9261","uuid":"aeb792b8-27b9-458d-86bf-01f8446ceddf","stig_uuid":"f79ea114-f8fc-4462-a57f-8e955b36a64c","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsServer2019_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 7C811937627F069A90074A88AB1264CC0C42BA22\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'Windows Server 2019 account lockout duration must be configured to 15 minutes or greater.' matches the expected value on the Windows Server 2019 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-205796","group_tree":[{"id":"V-205796","title":"SRG-OS-000341-GPOS-00132","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-205796","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000341-GPOS-00132","rule_id_src":"SV-205796r958752_rule","rule_id":"SV-205796","rule_version":"WN19-CC-000270","rule_title":"Windows Server 2019 Application event log size must be configured to 32768 KB or greater.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Administrative Templates >> Windows Components >> Event Log Service >> Application >> \"Specify the maximum log file size (KB)\" to \"Enabled\" with a \"Maximum Log Size (KB)\" of \"32768\" or greater.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"If the system is configured to write events directly to an audit server, this is NA.\n\nIf the following registry value does not exist or is not configured as specified, this is a finding:\n\nRegistry Hive: HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\nRegistry Path: \\SOFTWARE\\Policies\\Microsoft\\Windows\\EventLog\\Application\\\n\nValue Name: MaxSize\n\nType: REG_DWORD\nValue: 0x00008000 (32768) (or greater)","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Inadequate log size will cause the log to fill up quickly. This may prevent audit events from being recorded properly and require frequent attention by administrative personnel.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["SV-103265","V-93177","CCI-001849"],"reference_identifier":"1641","uuid":"6d5c6365-daab-480c-89a4-f4205398c6f0","stig_uuid":"f79ea114-f8fc-4462-a57f-8e955b36a64c","status":"not_reviewed","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":""},{"group_id_src":"V-205797","group_tree":[{"id":"V-205797","title":"SRG-OS-000341-GPOS-00132","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-205797","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000341-GPOS-00132","rule_id_src":"SV-205797r1186384_rule","rule_id":"SV-205797","rule_version":"WN19-CC-000280","rule_title":"Windows Server 2019 security event log size must be configured to a value that holds at least one week's worth of audit records.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Administrative Templates >> Windows Components >> Event Log Service >> Security >> \"Specify the maximum log file size (KB)\" to \"Enabled\" with a \"Maximum Log Size (KB)\" of a value that will contain one week of audit records or greater.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"If the system is configured to write events directly to an audit server, this is not applicable.\n\nThe registry configuration setting below must be set (at least) to a value equal to the size needed to contain one week's worth of audit records in the security event log. The value used below is an example that assumes a typical week\u2019s log size of 5GB.\n\nIf the following registry value does not exist or is not configured as specified, this is a finding:\n\nNote: The following registry entry is an example; the value must equal at least one week's worth of records.\n\nRegistry Hive: HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\nRegistry Path: \\SOFTWARE\\Policies\\Microsoft\\Windows\\EventLog\\Security\\\n\nValue Name: MaxSize\n\nType: REG_DWORD\nValue:0x49960800 (5120000) (or greater)","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Inadequate log size will cause the log to fill up quickly. This may prevent audit events from being recorded properly and require frequent attention by administrative personnel. System administrators (SAs) must monitor the volume of security event audit records and increase the registry value for the log size as needed.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["SV-103267","V-93179","CCI-001849"],"reference_identifier":"1996","uuid":"e9828ce7-74a4-4c5a-bb91-ea20bc72da5d","stig_uuid":"f79ea114-f8fc-4462-a57f-8e955b36a64c","status":"not_reviewed","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":""},{"group_id_src":"V-205798","group_tree":[{"id":"V-205798","title":"SRG-OS-000341-GPOS-00132","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-205798","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000341-GPOS-00132","rule_id_src":"SV-205798r958752_rule","rule_id":"SV-205798","rule_version":"WN19-CC-000290","rule_title":"Windows Server 2019 System event log size must be configured to 32768 KB or greater.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Administrative Templates >> Windows Components >> Event Log Service >> System >> \"Specify the maximum log file size (KB)\" to \"Enabled\" with a \"Maximum Log Size (KB)\" of \"32768\" or greater.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"If the system is configured to write events directly to an audit server, this is NA.\n\nIf the following registry value does not exist or is not configured as specified, this is a finding:\n\nRegistry Hive: HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\nRegistry Path: \\SOFTWARE\\Policies\\Microsoft\\Windows\\EventLog\\System\\\n\nValue Name: MaxSize\n\nType: REG_DWORD\nValue: 0x00008000 (32768) (or greater)","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Inadequate log size will cause the log to fill up quickly. This may prevent audit events from being recorded properly and require frequent attention by administrative personnel.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["SV-103269","V-93181","CCI-001849"],"reference_identifier":"3705","uuid":"4b40216d-d742-4751-b0f6-43a81ac67c66","stig_uuid":"f79ea114-f8fc-4462-a57f-8e955b36a64c","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsServer2019_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 3FBCCD1011BB5CDD0D4512E9B7F27A74E47CC378\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'Windows Server 2019 System event log size must be configured to 32768 KB or greater.' matches the expected value on the Windows Server 2019 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-205799","group_tree":[{"id":"V-205799","title":"SRG-OS-000342-GPOS-00133","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-205799","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000342-GPOS-00133","rule_id_src":"SV-205799r958754_rule","rule_id":"SV-205799","rule_version":"WN19-AU-000010","rule_title":"Windows Server 2019 audit records must be backed up to a different system or media than the system being audited.","fix_text":"Establish and implement a process for backing up log data to another system or media other than the system being audited.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Determine if a process to back up log data to a different system or media than the system being audited has been implemented.\n\nIf it has not, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Protection of log data includes assuring the log data is not accidentally lost or deleted. Audit information stored in one location is vulnerable to accidental or incidental deletion or alteration.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["V-93183","SV-103271","CCI-001851"],"reference_identifier":"1597","uuid":"22221caf-dc34-4471-b359-41456fa8e6ff","stig_uuid":"f79ea114-f8fc-4462-a57f-8e955b36a64c","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsServer2019_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: D5D38C79872CBE67CA400513351ACBEE71A6CB71\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'Windows Server 2019 audit records must be backed up to a different system or media than the system being audited.' matches the expected value on the Windows Server 2019 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-205800","group_tree":[{"id":"V-205800","title":"SRG-OS-000355-GPOS-00143","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-205800","severity":"low","group_title":"SRG-OS-000355-GPOS-00143","rule_id_src":"SV-205800r1051077_rule","rule_id":"SV-205800","rule_version":"WN19-00-000440","rule_title":"The Windows Server 2019 time service must synchronize with an appropriate DOD time source.","fix_text":"Configure the system to synchronize time with an appropriate DOD time source.\n\nDomain-joined systems use NT5DS to synchronize time from other systems in the domain by default.\n\nIf the system needs to be configured to an NTP server, configure the system to point to an authorized time server by setting the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Administrative Templates >> System >> Windows Time Service >> Time Providers >> \"Configure Windows NTP Client\" to \"Enabled\", and configure the \"NtpServer\" field to point to an appropriate DOD time server.\n\nThe US Naval Observatory operates stratum 1 time servers, which are identified at:\nhttps://www.cnmoc.usff.navy.mil/Our-Commands/United-States-Naval-Observatory/Precise-Time-Department/Network-Time-Protocol-NTP/\n\nTime synchronization will occur through a hierarchy of time servers down to the local level. Clients and lower-level servers will synchronize with an authorized time server in the hierarchy.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review the Windows time service configuration.\n\nOpen an elevated \"Command Prompt\" (run as administrator).\n\nEnter \"W32tm /query /configuration\".\n\nDomain-joined systems (excluding the domain controller with the PDC emulator role):\n\nIf the value for \"Type\" under \"NTP Client\" is not \"NT5DS\", this is a finding.\n\nOther systems:\n\nIf systems are configured with a \"Type\" of \"NTP\", including standalone or nondomain-joined systems and the domain controller with the PDC Emulator role, and do not have a DOD time server defined for \"NTPServer\", this is a finding.\n\nTo determine the domain controller with the PDC Emulator role:\n\nOpen \"PowerShell\".\n\nEnter \"Get-ADDomain | FT PDCEmulator\".","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"The Windows Time Service controls time synchronization settings. Time synchronization is essential for authentication and auditing purposes. If the Windows Time Service is used, it must synchronize with a secure, authorized time source. Domain-joined systems are automatically configured to synchronize with domain controllers. If an NTP server is configured, it must synchronize with a secure, authorized time source.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["V-93187","SV-103275","CCI-004923","CCI-001891"],"reference_identifier":"3540","uuid":"4cfbe0a2-c3ac-49bc-97dd-f2811445edad","stig_uuid":"f79ea114-f8fc-4462-a57f-8e955b36a64c","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsServer2019_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 3B95C0A4F73105290C80F41A706A6080E5AFC468\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'The Windows Server 2019 time service must synchronize with an appropriate DOD time source.' matches the expected value on the Windows Server 2019 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-205801","group_tree":[{"id":"V-205801","title":"SRG-OS-000362-GPOS-00149","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-205801","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000362-GPOS-00149","rule_id_src":"SV-205801r1051078_rule","rule_id":"SV-205801","rule_version":"WN19-CC-000420","rule_title":"Windows Server 2019 must prevent users from changing installation options.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Administrative Templates >> Windows Components >> Windows Installer >> \"Allow user control over installs\" to \"Disabled\".","weight":"10.0","check_content":"If the following registry value does not exist or is not configured as specified, this is a finding:\n\nRegistry Hive: HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\nRegistry Path: \\SOFTWARE\\Policies\\Microsoft\\Windows\\Installer\\\n\nValue Name: EnableUserControl\n\nType: REG_DWORD\nValue: 0x00000000 (0)","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Installation options for applications are typically controlled by administrators. This setting prevents users from changing installation options that may bypass security features.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["V-93199","SV-103287","CCI-003980","CCI-001812"],"reference_identifier":"2684","uuid":"72eb5c49-00b7-40cd-a396-5f04377ad71b","stig_uuid":"f79ea114-f8fc-4462-a57f-8e955b36a64c","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"Not applicable - capability not installed/enabled on this asset.","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsServer2019_Checks) marked this Not_Applicable on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 60BA293D826B924C2AD08653ACD8B79FDFF3D450\r\n~~~~~\r\nThe feature/role addressed by 'Windows Server 2019 must prevent users from changing installation options.' is not present or not in use on this the Windows Server 2019 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-205802","group_tree":[{"id":"V-205802","title":"SRG-OS-000362-GPOS-00149","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-205802","severity":"high","group_title":"SRG-OS-000362-GPOS-00149","rule_id_src":"SV-205802r1051079_rule","rule_id":"SV-205802","rule_version":"WN19-CC-000430","rule_title":"Windows Server 2019 must disable the Windows Installer Always install with elevated privileges option.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Administrative Templates >> Windows Components >> Windows Installer >> \"Always install with elevated privileges\" to \"Disabled\".","weight":"10.0","check_content":"If the following registry value does not exist or is not configured as specified, this is a finding:\n\nRegistry Hive: HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\nRegistry Path: \\SOFTWARE\\Policies\\Microsoft\\Windows\\Installer\\\n\nValue Name: AlwaysInstallElevated\n\nType: REG_DWORD\nValue: 0x00000000 (0)","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Standard user accounts must not be granted elevated privileges. Enabling Windows Installer to elevate privileges when installing applications can allow malicious persons and applications to gain full control of a system.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["V-93201","SV-103289","CCI-003980","CCI-001812"],"reference_identifier":"2353","uuid":"66e1eacc-7340-4227-a5cf-fdc4e0eee657","stig_uuid":"f79ea114-f8fc-4462-a57f-8e955b36a64c","status":"not_reviewed","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":""},{"group_id_src":"V-205803","group_tree":[{"id":"V-205803","title":"SRG-OS-000363-GPOS-00150","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-205803","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000363-GPOS-00150","rule_id_src":"SV-205803r958794_rule","rule_id":"SV-205803","rule_version":"WN19-00-000220","rule_title":"Windows Server 2019 system files must be monitored for unauthorized changes.","fix_text":"Monitor the system for unauthorized changes to system files (e.g., *.exe, *.bat, *.com, *.cmd, and *.dll) against a baseline on a weekly basis. This can be done with the use of various monitoring tools.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Determine whether the system is monitored for unauthorized changes to system files (e.g., *.exe, *.bat, *.com, *.cmd, and *.dll) against a baseline on a weekly basis.\n\nIf system files are not monitored for unauthorized changes, this is a finding.\n\nAn approved and properly configured solution will contain both a list of baselines that includes all system file locations and a file comparison task that is scheduled to run at least weekly.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Monitoring system files for changes against a baseline on a regular basis may help detect the possible introduction of malicious code on a system.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["SV-103291","V-93203","CCI-001744"],"reference_identifier":"4639","uuid":"cff326ea-c6d1-4f06-b00a-097605d3fdd8","stig_uuid":"f79ea114-f8fc-4462-a57f-8e955b36a64c","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsServer2019_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: CAFEC15A240010733CC3DD89C0B8AF7A1CCE25DE\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'Windows Server 2019 system files must be monitored for unauthorized changes.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the Windows Server 2019 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-205804","group_tree":[{"id":"V-205804","title":"SRG-OS-000368-GPOS-00154","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-205804","severity":"high","group_title":"SRG-OS-000368-GPOS-00154","rule_id_src":"SV-205804r958804_rule","rule_id":"SV-205804","rule_version":"WN19-CC-000210","rule_title":"Windows Server 2019 Autoplay must be turned off for non-volume devices.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Administrative Templates >> Windows Components >> AutoPlay Policies >> \"Disallow Autoplay for non-volume devices\" to \"Enabled\".","weight":"10.0","check_content":"If the following registry value does not exist or is not configured as specified, this is a finding:\n\nRegistry Hive: HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\nRegistry Path: \\SOFTWARE\\Policies\\Microsoft\\Windows\\Explorer\\\n\nValue Name: NoAutoplayfornonVolume\n\nType: REG_DWORD\nValue: 0x00000001 (1)","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Allowing AutoPlay to execute may introduce malicious code to a system. AutoPlay begins reading from a drive as soon as media is inserted into the drive. As a result, the setup file of programs or music on audio media may start. This setting will disable AutoPlay for non-volume devices, such as Media Transfer Protocol (MTP) devices.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["V-93373","SV-103459","CCI-001764"],"reference_identifier":"5629","uuid":"bb461ae7-0edf-4542-a354-f0671afd1e62","stig_uuid":"f79ea114-f8fc-4462-a57f-8e955b36a64c","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsServer2019_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 76F8085EC6C4907C48F794081EE584C7AB7FBCAD\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'Windows Server 2019 Autoplay must be turned off for non-volume devices.' matches the expected value on the Windows Server 2019 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-205805","group_tree":[{"id":"V-205805","title":"SRG-OS-000368-GPOS-00154","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-205805","severity":"high","group_title":"SRG-OS-000368-GPOS-00154","rule_id_src":"SV-205805r958804_rule","rule_id":"SV-205805","rule_version":"WN19-CC-000220","rule_title":"Windows Server 2019 default AutoRun behavior must be configured to prevent AutoRun commands.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Administrative Templates >> Windows Components >> AutoPlay Policies >> \"Set the default behavior for AutoRun\" to \"Enabled\" with \"Do not execute any autorun commands\" selected.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"If the following registry value does not exist or is not configured as specified, this is a finding:\n\nRegistry Hive: HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\nRegistry Path: \\SOFTWARE\\Microsoft\\Windows\\CurrentVersion\\Policies\\Explorer\\\n\nValue Name: NoAutorun\n\nType: REG_DWORD\nValue: 0x00000001 (1)","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Allowing AutoRun commands to execute may introduce malicious code to a system. Configuring this setting prevents AutoRun commands from executing.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["V-93375","SV-103461","CCI-001764"],"reference_identifier":"9549","uuid":"d23525e4-cb4d-4c84-a4e9-a8fd298a2d63","stig_uuid":"f79ea114-f8fc-4462-a57f-8e955b36a64c","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsServer2019_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 5981322C6536419FF66DF4AE644CCCCFF50FC832\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'Windows Server 2019 default AutoRun behavior must be configured to prevent AutoRun commands.' matches the expected value on the Windows Server 2019 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-205806","group_tree":[{"id":"V-205806","title":"SRG-OS-000368-GPOS-00154","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-205806","severity":"high","group_title":"SRG-OS-000368-GPOS-00154","rule_id_src":"SV-205806r958804_rule","rule_id":"SV-205806","rule_version":"WN19-CC-000230","rule_title":"Windows Server 2019 AutoPlay must be disabled for all drives.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Administrative Templates >> Windows Components >> AutoPlay Policies >> \"Turn off AutoPlay\" to \"Enabled\" with \"All Drives\" selected.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"If the following registry value does not exist or is not configured as specified, this is a finding:\n\nRegistry Hive: HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\nRegistry Path:  \\SOFTWARE\\Microsoft\\Windows\\CurrentVersion\\policies\\Explorer\\\n\nValue Name: NoDriveTypeAutoRun\n\nType: REG_DWORD\nValue: 0x000000ff (255)","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Allowing AutoPlay to execute may introduce malicious code to a system. AutoPlay begins reading from a drive as soon media is inserted into the drive. As a result, the setup file of programs or music on audio media may start. By default, AutoPlay is disabled on removable drives, such as the floppy disk drive (but not the CD-ROM drive) and on network drives. Enabling this policy disables AutoPlay on all drives.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["V-93377","SV-103463","CCI-001764"],"reference_identifier":"8297","uuid":"e76e3690-ca64-42ec-8499-ee1136db91c3","stig_uuid":"f79ea114-f8fc-4462-a57f-8e955b36a64c","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsServer2019_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: E893661965AFAE9A52AA9E295246C4474521CAE2\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'Windows Server 2019 AutoPlay must be disabled for all drives.' matches the expected value on the Windows Server 2019 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-205807","group_tree":[{"id":"V-205807","title":"SRG-OS-000370-GPOS-00155","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-205807","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000370-GPOS-00155","rule_id_src":"SV-205807r958808_rule","rule_id":"SV-205807","rule_version":"WN19-00-000080","rule_title":"Windows Server 2019 must employ a deny-all, permit-by-exception policy to allow the execution of authorized software programs.","fix_text":"Configure an application allowlisting program to employ a deny-all, permit-by-exception policy to allow the execution of authorized software programs.\n\nConfiguration of allowlisting applications will vary by the program. AppLocker is an allowlisting application built into Windows Server.\n\nIf AppLocker is used, it is configured through group policy in Computer Configuration >> Windows Settings >> Security Settings >> Application Control Policies >> AppLocker.\n\nImplementation guidance for AppLocker is available at the following link:\n\nhttps://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/security/threat-protection/windows-defender-application-control/applocker/applocker-policies-deployment-guide","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the operating system employs a deny-all, permit-by-exception policy to allow the execution of authorized software programs.\n\nIf an application allowlisting program is not in use on the system, this is a finding.\n\nConfiguration of allowlisting applications will vary by the program.\n\nAppLocker is an allowlisting application built into Windows Server. A deny-by-default implementation is initiated by enabling any AppLocker rules within a category, only allowing what is specified by defined rules.\n\nIf AppLocker is used, perform the following to view the configuration of AppLocker:\n\nOpen \"PowerShell\".\n\nIf the AppLocker PowerShell module has not been imported previously, execute the following first:\n\nImport-Module AppLocker\n\nExecute the following command, substituting [c:\\temp\\file.xml] with a location and file name appropriate for the system:\n\nGet-AppLockerPolicy -Effective -XML > c:\\temp\\file.xml\n\nThis will produce an xml file with the effective settings that can be viewed in a browser or opened in a program such as Excel for review.\n\nImplementation guidance for AppLocker is available at the following link:\n\nhttps://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/security/threat-protection/windows-defender-application-control/applocker/applocker-policies-deployment-guide","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Using an allowlist provides a configuration management method to allow the execution of only authorized software. Using only authorized software decreases risk by limiting the number of potential vulnerabilities.\n\nThe organization must identify authorized software programs and only permit execution of authorized software. The process used to identify software programs that are authorized to execute on organizational information systems is commonly referred to as allowlisting.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["V-93379","SV-103465","CCI-001774"],"reference_identifier":"7039","uuid":"7f9d1649-e514-471f-a497-56f22ffd59ba","stig_uuid":"f79ea114-f8fc-4462-a57f-8e955b36a64c","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsServer2019_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 5033C711506A5B0535C0E0926C5FDB864ABF13B9\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'Windows Server 2019 must employ a deny-all, permit-by-exception policy to allow the execution of authorized software programs.' matches the expected value on the Windows Server 2019 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-205808","group_tree":[{"id":"V-205808","title":"SRG-OS-000373-GPOS-00157","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-205808","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000373-GPOS-00157","rule_id_src":"SV-205808r1051080_rule","rule_id":"SV-205808","rule_version":"WN19-CC-000340","rule_title":"Windows Server 2019 must not save passwords in the Remote Desktop Client.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Administrative Templates >> Windows Components >> Remote Desktop Services >> Remote Desktop Connection Client >> \"Do not allow passwords to be saved\" to \"Enabled\".","weight":"10.0","check_content":"If the following registry value does not exist or is not configured as specified, this is a finding:\n\nRegistry Hive: HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\nRegistry Path: \\SOFTWARE\\Policies\\Microsoft\\Windows NT\\Terminal Services\\\n\nValue Name: DisablePasswordSaving\n\nType: REG_DWORD\nValue: 0x00000001 (1)","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Saving passwords in the Remote Desktop Client could allow an unauthorized user to establish a remote desktop session to another system. The system must be configured to prevent users from saving passwords in the Remote Desktop Client.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000373-GPOS-00157, SRG-OS-000373-GPOS-00156","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["V-93425","SV-103511","CCI-002038"],"reference_identifier":"7588","uuid":"f52a9e41-5395-4605-b041-e1964c650e9f","stig_uuid":"f79ea114-f8fc-4462-a57f-8e955b36a64c","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsServer2019_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: C973A43DD5E6374D39EA5BCFD35D0E90636F9AC6\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'Windows Server 2019 must not save passwords in the Remote Desktop Client.' matches the expected value on the Windows Server 2019 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-205809","group_tree":[{"id":"V-205809","title":"SRG-OS-000373-GPOS-00157","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-205809","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000373-GPOS-00157","rule_id_src":"SV-205809r1051081_rule","rule_id":"SV-205809","rule_version":"WN19-CC-000360","rule_title":"Windows Server 2019 Remote Desktop Services must always prompt a client for passwords upon connection.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Administrative Templates >> Windows Components >> Remote Desktop Services >> Remote Desktop Session Host >> Security >> \"Always prompt for password upon connection\" to \"Enabled\".","weight":"10.0","check_content":"If the following registry value does not exist or is not configured as specified, this is a finding:\n\nRegistry Hive: HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\nRegistry Path: \\SOFTWARE\\Policies\\Microsoft\\Windows NT\\Terminal Services\\\n\nValue Name: fPromptForPassword\n\nType: REG_DWORD\nValue: 0x00000001 (1)","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"This setting controls the ability of users to supply passwords automatically as part of their remote desktop connection. Disabling this setting would allow anyone to use the stored credentials in a connection item to connect to the terminal server.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000373-GPOS-00157, SRG-OS-000373-GPOS-00156","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["V-93427","SV-103513","CCI-002038"],"reference_identifier":"5211","uuid":"e305cf12-66ba-4359-93f3-ba63669b5247","stig_uuid":"f79ea114-f8fc-4462-a57f-8e955b36a64c","status":"not_reviewed","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":""},{"group_id_src":"V-205810","group_tree":[{"id":"V-205810","title":"SRG-OS-000373-GPOS-00157","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-205810","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000373-GPOS-00157","rule_id_src":"SV-205810r1051082_rule","rule_id":"SV-205810","rule_version":"WN19-CC-000520","rule_title":"Windows Server 2019 Windows Remote Management (WinRM) service must not store RunAs credentials.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Administrative Templates >> Windows Components >> Windows Remote Management (WinRM) >> WinRM Service >> \"Disallow WinRM from storing RunAs credentials\" to \"Enabled\".","weight":"10.0","check_content":"If the following registry value does not exist or is not configured as specified, this is a finding:\n\nRegistry Hive: HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\nRegistry Path: \\SOFTWARE\\Policies\\Microsoft\\Windows\\WinRM\\Service\\\n\nValue Name: DisableRunAs\n\nType: REG_DWORD\nValue: 0x00000001 (1)","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Storage of administrative credentials could allow unauthorized access. Disallowing the storage of RunAs credentials for Windows Remote Management will prevent them from being used with plug-ins.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000373-GPOS-00157, SRG-OS-000373-GPOS-00156","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["SV-103515","V-93429","CCI-002038"],"reference_identifier":"8902","uuid":"ce20548e-4bde-45c3-8f9c-6d884f877200","stig_uuid":"f79ea114-f8fc-4462-a57f-8e955b36a64c","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"Not applicable - capability not installed/enabled on this asset.","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsServer2019_Checks) marked this Not_Applicable on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 8591DC002AFAF4951BE110D5A9BAAD388E211456\r\n~~~~~\r\nThe feature/role addressed by 'Windows Server 2019 Windows Remote Management (WinRM) service must not store RunAs credentials.' is not present or not in use on this the Windows Server 2019 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-205811","group_tree":[{"id":"V-205811","title":"SRG-OS-000373-GPOS-00157","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-205811","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000373-GPOS-00157","rule_id_src":"SV-205811r1051083_rule","rule_id":"SV-205811","rule_version":"WN19-SO-000380","rule_title":"Windows Server 2019 User Account Control approval mode for the built-in Administrator must be enabled.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Windows Settings >> Security Settings >> Local Policies >> Security Options >> \"User Account Control: Admin Approval Mode for the Built-in Administrator account\" to \"Enabled\".","weight":"10.0","check_content":"UAC requirements are NA for Server Core installations (this is the default installation option for Windows Server 2019 versus Server with Desktop Experience).\n\nIf the following registry value does not exist or is not configured as specified, this is a finding:\n\nRegistry Hive: HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE \nRegistry Path: \\SOFTWARE\\Microsoft\\Windows\\CurrentVersion\\Policies\\System\\\n\nValue Name: FilterAdministratorToken\n\nValue Type: REG_DWORD\nValue: 0x00000001 (1)","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"User Account Control (UAC) is a security mechanism for limiting the elevation of privileges, including administrative accounts, unless authorized. This setting configures the built-in Administrator account so that it runs in Admin Approval Mode.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000373-GPOS-00157, SRG-OS-000373-GPOS-00156","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["SV-103517","V-93431","CCI-002038"],"reference_identifier":"2710","uuid":"4be7eed6-e329-4609-8af3-089cee475c16","stig_uuid":"f79ea114-f8fc-4462-a57f-8e955b36a64c","status":"not_reviewed","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":""},{"group_id_src":"V-205812","group_tree":[{"id":"V-205812","title":"SRG-OS-000373-GPOS-00157","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-205812","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000373-GPOS-00157","rule_id_src":"SV-205812r1051084_rule","rule_id":"SV-205812","rule_version":"WN19-SO-000410","rule_title":"Windows Server 2019 User Account Control must automatically deny standard user requests for elevation.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Windows Settings >> Security Settings >> Local Policies >> Security Options >> \"User Account Control: Behavior of the elevation prompt for standard users\" to \"Automatically deny elevation requests\".","weight":"10.0","check_content":"UAC requirements are NA for Server Core installations (this is the default installation option for Windows Server 2019 versus Server with Desktop Experience).\n\nIf the following registry value does not exist or is not configured as specified, this is a finding:\n\nRegistry Hive: HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE \nRegistry Path: \\SOFTWARE\\Microsoft\\Windows\\CurrentVersion\\Policies\\System\\\n\nValue Name: ConsentPromptBehaviorUser\n\nValue Type: REG_DWORD\nValue: 0x00000000 (0)","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"User Account Control (UAC) is a security mechanism for limiting the elevation of privileges, including administrative accounts, unless authorized. This setting controls the behavior of elevation when requested by a standard user account.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000373-GPOS-00157, SRG-OS-000373-GPOS-00156","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["V-93433","SV-103519","CCI-002038"],"reference_identifier":"3598","uuid":"da49aea2-0d62-4044-9497-f8e6f04cf3f3","stig_uuid":"f79ea114-f8fc-4462-a57f-8e955b36a64c","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsServer2019_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 43005A9069D0F699981B0AE660585B9E4AA9C458\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'Windows Server 2019 User Account Control must automatically deny standard user requests for elevation.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the Windows Server 2019 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-205813","group_tree":[{"id":"V-205813","title":"SRG-OS-000373-GPOS-00157","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-205813","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000373-GPOS-00157","rule_id_src":"SV-205813r1051085_rule","rule_id":"SV-205813","rule_version":"WN19-SO-000440","rule_title":"Windows Server 2019 User Account Control must run all administrators in Admin Approval Mode, enabling UAC.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Windows Settings >> Security Settings >> Local Policies >> Security Options >> \"User Account Control: Run all administrators in Admin Approval Mode\" to \"Enabled\".","weight":"10.0","check_content":"UAC requirements are NA for Server Core installations (this is the default installation option for Windows Server 2019 versus Server with Desktop Experience).\n\nIf the following registry value does not exist or is not configured as specified, this is a finding:\n\nRegistry Hive: HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE \nRegistry Path: \\SOFTWARE\\Microsoft\\Windows\\CurrentVersion\\Policies\\System\\\n\nValue Name: EnableLUA\n\nValue Type: REG_DWORD\nValue: 0x00000001 (1)","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"User Account Control (UAC) is a security mechanism for limiting the elevation of privileges, including administrative accounts, unless authorized. This setting enables UAC.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000373-GPOS-00157, SRG-OS-000373-GPOS-00156","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["V-93435","SV-103521","CCI-002038"],"reference_identifier":"3854","uuid":"c3ad8689-4f7c-45ef-af33-0a9ff4eb0d83","stig_uuid":"f79ea114-f8fc-4462-a57f-8e955b36a64c","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsServer2019_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 9104318D2E270AF3B246F837BEEE70F2F34FAD1E\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'Windows Server 2019 User Account Control must run all administrators in Admin Approval Mode, enabling UAC.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the Windows Server 2019 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-205814","group_tree":[{"id":"V-205814","title":"SRG-OS-000379-GPOS-00164","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-205814","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000379-GPOS-00164","rule_id_src":"SV-205814r971545_rule","rule_id":"SV-205814","rule_version":"WN19-MS-000040","rule_title":"Windows Server 2019 must restrict unauthenticated Remote Procedure Call (RPC) clients from connecting to the RPC server on domain-joined member servers and standalone or nondomain-joined systems.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Administrative Templates >> System >> Remote Procedure Call >> \"Restrict Unauthenticated RPC clients\" to \"Enabled\" with \"Authenticated\" selected.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"This applies to member servers and standalone or nondomain-joined systems. It is NA for domain controllers.\n\nIf the following registry value does not exist or is not configured as specified, this is a finding:\n\nRegistry Hive:  HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\nRegistry Path:  \\SOFTWARE\\Policies\\Microsoft\\Windows NT\\Rpc\\\n\nValue Name:  RestrictRemoteClients\n\nType:  REG_DWORD\nValue:  0x00000001 (1)","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Unauthenticated RPC clients may allow anonymous access to sensitive information. Configuring RPC to restrict unauthenticated RPC clients from connecting to the RPC server will prevent anonymous connections.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["V-93453","SV-103539","CCI-001967"],"reference_identifier":"5387","uuid":"49a567b0-158a-4429-842f-b3cbbfd6c696","stig_uuid":"f79ea114-f8fc-4462-a57f-8e955b36a64c","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsServer2019_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: E6DD2CC7AEBED0FA30077D452B2CE96D0F307197\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'Windows Server 2019 must restrict unauthenticated Remote Procedure Call (RPC) clients from connecting to the RPC server on domain-joined member servers and standalone or nondomain-joined systems.' matches the expected value on the Windows Server 2019 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-205815","group_tree":[{"id":"V-205815","title":"SRG-OS-000379-GPOS-00164","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-205815","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000379-GPOS-00164","rule_id_src":"SV-205815r971545_rule","rule_id":"SV-205815","rule_version":"WN19-SO-000090","rule_title":"Windows Server 2019 computer account password must not be prevented from being reset.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Windows Settings >> Security Settings >> Local Policies >> Security Options >> \"Domain member: Disable machine account password changes\" to \"Disabled\".","weight":"10.0","check_content":"If the following registry value does not exist or is not configured as specified, this is a finding:\n\nRegistry Hive: HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE \nRegistry Path: \\SYSTEM\\CurrentControlSet\\Services\\Netlogon\\Parameters\\\n\nValue Name: DisablePasswordChange\n\nValue Type: REG_DWORD\nValue: 0x00000000 (0)","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Computer account passwords are changed automatically on a regular basis. Disabling automatic password changes can make the system more vulnerable to malicious access. Frequent password changes can be a significant safeguard for the system. A new password for the computer account will be generated every 30 days.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["V-93455","SV-103541","CCI-001967"],"reference_identifier":"1545","uuid":"363aa861-ae68-4afd-b49b-d00295450745","stig_uuid":"f79ea114-f8fc-4462-a57f-8e955b36a64c","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsServer2019_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 91BD6B077F08EA9684D24B872A7B43D0D9FE43CC\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'Windows Server 2019 computer account password must not be prevented from being reset.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the Windows Server 2019 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-205816","group_tree":[{"id":"V-205816","title":"SRG-OS-000393-GPOS-00173","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-205816","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000393-GPOS-00173","rule_id_src":"SV-205816r958848_rule","rule_id":"SV-205816","rule_version":"WN19-CC-000480","rule_title":"Windows Server 2019 Windows Remote Management (WinRM) client must not allow unencrypted traffic.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Administrative Templates >> Windows Components >> Windows Remote Management (WinRM) >> WinRM Client >> \"Allow unencrypted traffic\" to \"Disabled\".","weight":"10.0","check_content":"If the following registry value does not exist or is not configured as specified, this is a finding:\n\nRegistry Hive: HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\nRegistry Path: \\SOFTWARE\\Policies\\Microsoft\\Windows\\WinRM\\Client\\\n\nValue Name: AllowUnencryptedTraffic\n\nType: REG_DWORD\nValue: 0x00000000 (0)","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Unencrypted remote access to a system can allow sensitive information to be compromised. Windows remote management connections must be encrypted to prevent this.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000393-GPOS-00173, SRG-OS-000394-GPOS-00174","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["SV-103585","V-93499","CCI-002890","CCI-003123"],"reference_identifier":"1173","uuid":"7f58300e-7da4-4c82-b643-4b1a75b4cb5d","stig_uuid":"f79ea114-f8fc-4462-a57f-8e955b36a64c","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsServer2019_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: DE39F76B09B19A8DBEC4055A3E8B9B3935C166A9\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'Windows Server 2019 Windows Remote Management (WinRM) client must not allow unencrypted traffic.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the Windows Server 2019 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-205817","group_tree":[{"id":"V-205817","title":"SRG-OS-000393-GPOS-00173","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-205817","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000393-GPOS-00173","rule_id_src":"SV-205817r958848_rule","rule_id":"SV-205817","rule_version":"WN19-CC-000510","rule_title":"Windows Server 2019 Windows Remote Management (WinRM) service must not allow unencrypted traffic.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Administrative Templates >> Windows Components >> Windows Remote Management (WinRM) >> WinRM Service >> \"Allow unencrypted traffic\" to \"Disabled\".","weight":"10.0","check_content":"If the following registry value does not exist or is not configured as specified, this is a finding:\n\nRegistry Hive: HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\nRegistry Path: \\SOFTWARE\\Policies\\Microsoft\\Windows\\WinRM\\Service\\\n\nValue Name: AllowUnencryptedTraffic\n\nType: REG_DWORD\nValue: 0x00000000 (0)","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Unencrypted remote access to a system can allow sensitive information to be compromised. Windows remote management connections must be encrypted to prevent this.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000393-GPOS-00173, SRG-OS-000394-GPOS-00174","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["SV-103587","V-93501","CCI-002890","CCI-003123"],"reference_identifier":"2709","uuid":"00acb3db-a42f-4edd-915b-cf2a77dcd68d","stig_uuid":"f79ea114-f8fc-4462-a57f-8e955b36a64c","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsServer2019_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 0229CC29BE65A45CC8F5B5EF348511ADAD36C30A\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'Windows Server 2019 Windows Remote Management (WinRM) service must not allow unencrypted traffic.' matches the expected value on the Windows Server 2019 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-205818","group_tree":[{"id":"V-205818","title":"SRG-OS-000396-GPOS-00176","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-205818","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000396-GPOS-00176","rule_id_src":"SV-205818r987791_rule","rule_id":"SV-205818","rule_version":"WN19-DC-000140","rule_title":"Windows Server 2019 must use separate, NSA-approved (Type 1) cryptography to protect the directory data in transit for directory service implementations at a classified confidentiality level when replication data traverses a network cleared to a lower level than the data.","fix_text":"Configure NSA-approved (Type 1) cryptography to protect the directory data in transit for directory service implementations at a classified confidentiality level that transfer replication data through a network cleared to a lower level than the data.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"This applies to domain controllers. It is NA for other systems.\n\nReview the organization network diagram(s) or documentation to determine the level of classification for the network(s) over which replication data is transmitted.\n\nDetermine the classification level of the Windows domain controller.\n\nIf the classification level of the Windows domain controller is higher than the level of the networks, review the organization network diagram(s) and directory implementation documentation to determine if NSA-approved encryption is used to protect the replication network traffic.\n\nIf the classification level of the Windows domain controller is higher than the level of the network traversed and NSA-approved encryption is not used, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Directory data that is not appropriately encrypted is subject to compromise. Commercial-grade encryption does not provide adequate protection when the classification level of directory data in transit is higher than the level of the network.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["V-93513","SV-103599","CCI-002450"],"reference_identifier":"4503","uuid":"b11ed256-d308-4678-93ab-bf501cabf5a7","stig_uuid":"f79ea114-f8fc-4462-a57f-8e955b36a64c","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsServer2019_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 5B78B6220EF3D477C35A279DF823D8B063581225\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'Windows Server 2019 must use separate, NSA-approved (Type 1) cryptography to protect the directory data in transit for directory service implementations at a classified confidentiality level when replication data traverses a network cleared to a lower level than the data.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the Windows Server 2019 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-205819","group_tree":[{"id":"V-205819","title":"SRG-OS-000420-GPOS-00186","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-205819","severity":"low","group_title":"SRG-OS-000420-GPOS-00186","rule_id_src":"SV-205819r958902_rule","rule_id":"SV-205819","rule_version":"WN19-CC-000060","rule_title":"Windows Server 2019 must be configured to ignore NetBIOS name release requests except from WINS servers.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Administrative Templates >> MSS (Legacy) >> \"MSS: (NoNameReleaseOnDemand) Allow the computer to ignore NetBIOS name release requests except from WINS servers\" to \"Enabled\".\n\nThis policy setting requires the installation of the MSS-Legacy custom templates included with the STIG package. \"MSS-Legacy.admx\" and \"MSS-Legacy.adml\" must be copied to the \\Windows\\PolicyDefinitions and \\Windows\\PolicyDefinitions\\en-US directories respectively.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"If the following registry value does not exist or is not configured as specified, this is a finding:\n\nRegistry Hive:  HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\nRegistry Path:  \\SYSTEM\\CurrentControlSet\\Services\\Netbt\\Parameters\\\n\nValue Name:  NoNameReleaseOnDemand\n\nValue Type:  REG_DWORD\nValue:  0x00000001 (1)","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Configuring the system to ignore name release requests, except from WINS servers, prevents a denial of service (DoS) attack. The DoS consists of sending a NetBIOS name release request to the server for each entry in the server's cache, causing a response delay in the normal operation of the server's WINS resolution capability.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["SV-103627","V-93541","CCI-002385"],"reference_identifier":"8746","uuid":"b247f888-46a5-4d7c-b99e-2906243aa499","stig_uuid":"f79ea114-f8fc-4462-a57f-8e955b36a64c","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsServer2019_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: F0F62CE1A6F05CAC067EAF7E74C17E3CE332F7E8\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'Windows Server 2019 must be configured to ignore NetBIOS name release requests except from WINS servers.' matches the expected value on the Windows Server 2019 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-205820","group_tree":[{"id":"V-205820","title":"SRG-OS-000423-GPOS-00187","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-205820","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000423-GPOS-00187","rule_id_src":"SV-205820r958908_rule","rule_id":"SV-205820","rule_version":"WN19-DC-000320","rule_title":"Windows Server 2019 domain controllers must require LDAP access signing.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Windows Settings >> Security Settings >> Local Policies >> Security Options >> \"Domain controller: LDAP server signing requirements\" to \"Require signing\".","weight":"10.0","check_content":"This applies to domain controllers. It is NA for other systems.\n\nIf the following registry value does not exist or is not configured as specified, this is a finding:\n\nRegistry Hive: HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE \nRegistry Path: \\SYSTEM\\CurrentControlSet\\Services\\NTDS\\Parameters\\\n\nValue Name: LDAPServerIntegrity\n\nValue Type: REG_DWORD\nValue: 0x00000002 (2)","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Unsigned network traffic is susceptible to man-in-the-middle attacks, where an intruder captures packets between the server and the client and modifies them before forwarding them to the client. In the case of an LDAP server, this means that an attacker could cause a client to make decisions based on false records from the LDAP directory. The risk of an attacker pulling this off can be decreased by implementing strong physical security measures to protect the network infrastructure. Furthermore, implementing Internet Protocol security (IPsec) authentication header mode (AH), which performs mutual authentication and packet integrity for Internet Protocol (IP) traffic, can make all types of man-in-the-middle attacks extremely difficult.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000423-GPOS-00187, SRG-OS-000424-GPOS-00188","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["V-93545","SV-103631","CCI-002418","CCI-002421"],"reference_identifier":"3325","uuid":"abbd65af-5483-479c-bb8c-d3ab9dbe7648","stig_uuid":"f79ea114-f8fc-4462-a57f-8e955b36a64c","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsServer2019_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: D3333956B625086EAF35CCC27518ECCAF23BB9E0\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'Windows Server 2019 domain controllers must require LDAP access signing.' matches the expected value on the Windows Server 2019 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-205821","group_tree":[{"id":"V-205821","title":"SRG-OS-000423-GPOS-00187","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-205821","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000423-GPOS-00187","rule_id_src":"SV-205821r958908_rule","rule_id":"SV-205821","rule_version":"WN19-SO-000060","rule_title":"Windows Server 2019 setting Domain member: Digitally encrypt or sign secure channel data (always) must be configured to Enabled.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Windows Settings >> Security Settings >> Local Policies >> Security Options >> \"Domain member: Digitally encrypt or sign secure channel data (always)\" to \"Enabled\".","weight":"10.0","check_content":"If the following registry value does not exist or is not configured as specified, this is a finding:\n\nRegistry Hive: HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE \nRegistry Path: \\SYSTEM\\CurrentControlSet\\Services\\Netlogon\\Parameters\\\n\nValue Name: RequireSignOrSeal\n\nValue Type: REG_DWORD\nValue: 0x00000001 (1)","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2019_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Requests sent on the secure channel are authenticated, and sensitive information (such as passwords) is encrypted, but not all information is encrypted. If this policy is enabled, outgoing secure channel traffic will be encrypted and signed.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000423-GPOS-00187, SRG-OS-000424-GPOS-00188","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["V-93547","SV-103633","CCI-002418","CCI-002421"],"reference_identifier":"6340","uuid":"59547bc0-846a-4a43-8cd9-0b753b7ab360","stig_uuid":"f79ea114-f8fc-4462-a57f-8e955b36a64c","status":"not_reviewed","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":""},{"group_id_src":"V-205822","group_tree":[{"id":"V-205822","title":"SRG-OS-000423-GPOS-00187","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-205822","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000423-GPOS-00187","rule_id_src":"SV-205822r958908_rule","rule_id":"SV-205822","rule_version":"WN19-SO-000070","rule_title":"Windows Server 2019 setting Domain member: Digitally encrypt secure channel data (when possible) must be configured to enabled.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Windows Settings >> Security Settings >> Local Policies >> Security Options >> \"Domain member: Digitally encrypt secure channel data (when possible)\" to \"Enabled\".","weight":"10.0","check_content":"If the following registry value does not exist or is not configured as specified, this is a finding:\n\nRegistry Hive: HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\nRegistry Path: \\SYSTEM\\CurrentControlSet\\Services\\Netlogon\\Parameters\\\n\nValue Name: SealSecureChannel\n\nValue Type: REG_DWORD\nValue: 0x00000001 (1)","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Wi